* linux i2c stack (software layer)

Layer     Name                Responsibility
=====     ==========          ======================== 
Top       I2C Device Driver   "The ""Waiter."" 
                              Knows what the specific sensor (like an MPU6050) needs and asks the bus for it."
Middle    I2C Core            "The ""Kitchen."" 
                              A generic layer that handles the passing of messages between drivers and hardware."
Bottom    I2C Adapter (Bus)   "The ""Chef."" 
                              The actual hardware on your Raspberry Pi (Broadcom chip) that wiggles the SDA/SCL lines."

                              
* Anatomy of an I2C Transaction
Every conversation on the bus follows a strict protocol:

START Condition: Master pulls SDA low while SCL is high.

Address + R/W Bit: "Hey, Device 0x68, I want to WRITE to you."

ACK (Acknowledge): The slave pulls SDA low to say, "I'm here!"

Data Transfer: Sending or receiving 8 bits at a time.

STOP Condition: Master releases the lines.


